Snipara uses a strict layered (clean/“onion”-style) architecture with a single allowed import direction and clearly separated responsibilities.

Core layers (top → bottom)
- Routes (apps/web/src/app/api/) — Thin HTTP handlers. Must:
  - Authenticate (requireAuth)
  - Validate input (Zod)
  - Delegate work to services or repository functions
  - Return a handled response
  - Example pattern:
    export async function POST(request: Request) {
      try {
        const user = await requireAuth();
        const body = schema.parse(await request.json());
        const result = await someService(body, user.id);
        return successResponse(result);
      } catch (error) {
        return handleError(error);
      }
    }

- Jobs / Orchestrators (lib/jobs/) — background processors / orchestration (can be imported by routes).

- Services (lib/services/) — External API adapters (e.g., Stripe). Use lazy initialization and retry logic; services talk to outside systems and are called from routes or jobs.

- Repositories (lib/db/queries/) — Centralized CRUD and permission-checked DB access. All DB access must go through this layer (never call Prisma directly from routes). Example: getProjectById(id, userId) enforces team membership.

- Types & Utils (types/, lib/utils/) — Shared pure utilities and type definitions. They must not depend on any other layer.

Key rules
- Import direction is one-way: higher layers can import lower layers, but lower layers cannot import higher layers.
- types/ and utils/ have no dependencies on other layers.
- All database queries live in lib/db/queries/ and include permission checks.
- Route handlers must be thin and delegate business logic to services/repositories.

Import hierarchy (from docs)
Routes (app/api/)
  ↓ imports
Services (lib/services/)
  ↓ imports
Repositories (lib/db/queries/)
  ↓ imports
Utils & Types — No dependencies

In short: a strict layered/clean-architecture pattern (Routes → Services → Repositories → Utils/Types) with enforced responsibilities and one-way imports.
